<br>
(a) If you can't open the case and identify every part, then get a name brand machine.  The extra money you spend purchasing a Dell (or whomever) is worth it the second a SINGLE thing goes wrong.<br>
<br>
(b) If you can identify parts and can tell the difference between a dead hard drive and bad memory, use a reputable online reseller like <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.newegg.com">Newegg</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
<br>
(c) If you can assemble every part yourself, and feel completely comfortable putting heat-sink grease on your processor yourself, and know exactly what program you plan on using to test your memory, then take your time and use a combination of <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.pricewatch.com">Pricewatch</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and your local paper/stores to put together a computer a hundred dollars cheaper than Newegg.<br>
<br>
Some other rules of thumb.  Shipping is less than tax.  You might want to buy your monitor local for a few reasons (especially if it's an LCD display).  It's an item that shipping might NOT be less than tax, for startes.  Dead pixel policies on LCDs.  Return hassles.  Buy your monitor where you can see it.<br>
<br>
When in doubt, buy more memory.  DDR is nice, but if you're on a budget, you'll be happy with a gig of PC133 over a much smaller ammount of DDR.  Half-gig sticks of DDR2100 are $100 right now, and Half-gig sticks of PC133 are 25.  There are still a number of motherboards that support both types of memory (not at the same time) where you can upgrade later.<br>
<br>
Don't buy the fastest processor out there.  While this isn't a great guide, an Athlon XP2400 is $199.  An XP2000 is $99.  You don't have to be a math major to figure out that the XP2400 isn't twice as fast as an XP2000 for twice the price.  Same deal applies to Intel.  P4-2.8 for $472.  P4-2.2 for $184.  Do the math.  Don't buy at the cutting edge unless your wallet can support it.<br>
<br>
A P4-2.8Ghz with a gig of DDR is $672.<br>
An XP2000 with a gig of PC133 is $149.<br>
Settle somewhere inbetween.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> An XP2200 or a P4-2.4 is about where the price/performance curve gets steep.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
You're gong to be playing games.  If you insist on sinking your money somewhere, get a GREAT video card.  Tell yourself the truth and get AT LEAST a GeForce4 Ti4200 with 128 megs for $114 (shipped).  That's your MINIMUM.<br>
<br>
If you piece it together yourself, of if you have somplace build it for you, I'll tell you right now, DO NOT CHEAT YOURSELF ON COOLING.  Today's machines run hot.  Spend the extra couple bucks on a real fan.<br>
<br>
